  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Saving Lives and Protecting Dignity of People affected by Drought 2018 in Afghanistan</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to provide immediate and short term support to 5,500 drought-affected families (38,500 individuals) in their place of origin so as to contribute to the prevention of drought-induced displacement as well as male labor migration in search for livelihoods and income-generating opportunities in major cities. DRC plans to distribute cash for food to 2,500 vulnerable families in remote locations of 8 targeted districts badly hit by drought to enable them to mitigate the cost of buying food products without compromising their future livelihoods or falling in debt or selling asset or taking any other harmful coping strategy. DRC will also distribute cash for fodder to 1,500 farmers who cannot feed their livestock (i.e. their major asset and source of their livelihoods) due to shortage of natural sources of feed to enable them retain their animals by purchasing fodder from the market. In addition, DRC plans to distribute wheat seeds or cash equivalent to 1,500 small/marginal farmers who intend to cultivate wheat in the upcoming winter season and protect them from adopting negative coping mechanism to do so.

In complementing this project, DRC (through other sources) will provide Psychological First Aid (PFA), Psycho-Social Support (PSS) and legal counseling to children and women at risk or survivors of rights violations and GBV through its existing Community Information and Multi-Service Centers (CIMS) and 4 newly established mobile clinics (2 in each province). In line with the above and building on its existing projects, DRC will provide safe spaces for children to play, learn, grow and develop. 

The proposed project duration is nine months from 16th August, 2018 to 15th May 2019.</narrative>
  </description>
